<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Living Dangerously; Have Fish Had Their Chips (BBC1, 8.30) takes an
old-fashioned anthropomorphic look at the seal, one of the many sea animals
in competition with fishermen.
The Dog's Tale (BBC2, 9.30) continues to turn up good things, albeit in a
disjointed fashion. Tonight investigates canine ESP, which many dog-lovers
swear by.
One of them is a woman whose dog, oddly named Ribbon (because he is a
bow-wow?) is apparently able to predict when she is about to have an
epileptic fit.
Connoisseurs of religious ritual may want to stay up to watch Relighting the
Candle (BBC1, 11.35), a ceremony which takes place at Bevis Marks, the
oldest synagogue in Britain. The spiritual home of the Sephardic Jews in
this country, Bevis Marks has twice been damaged by IRA explosions in the
City. Notables will be attending, not least Alan Yentob, the controller of
BBC1.
Midnight Jazz (BBC 2, 12.00) features McCoy Turner and the highly regarded
Julian Joseph quartet, followed by Arena profile of Billie Holiday
(repeat),(BBC 2, 12.40).
