<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / Mortgage scheme for council tenants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SCHEME to give council tenants a new way to buy their homes was launched
yesterday by Sir George Young, the housing minister.
The rents-to-mortgages initiative is aimed at about 1.4m council tenants who
pay full rent, as well as secure tenants of non-charitable housing
associations.
The scheme, previously tested in three pilot projects in 1991, allows
tenants to buy their homes by making an initial payment which is less than
the right-to-buy price. The rest of the cost does not have to be paid until
later, with mortgage repayments based on present rent levels.
Tenants paying Pounds 30 a week on a house valued at Pounds 50,000 for
example, would pay two-thirds of the right-to-buy price of Pounds 30,000,
based on their weekly rent. The tenant would then pay off the final third,
less a further discount, when the property is sold.
The campaign comes amid concerns about the position of council tenants who
have bought their homes but now find it difficult to sell, or who have had
problems in getting a mortgage.
A report from the Labour-dominated Association of London Authorities said
that local branches of banks and building societies were reluctant to lend
against ex-council flats, which were not seen as generally desirable
properties.
Mr John Battle, Labour's housing spokesman, said the scheme would not help
'the thousands of council leaseholders who are effectively trapped in homes
they cannot sell and cannot afford to renovate'.
There is also anxiety about the impact of any rise in interest rates on
those people targeted by the new initiative.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing analyst at UBS, said that unless people were
properly warned about possible increases in interest rates, then the
'rents-to-mortgages scheme could turn into a rents-to-repossessions scheme'.
Shelter, the housing charity, said that with one-in-12 mortgages in arrears
and 300,000 with arrears of six months or more, it was worried that
low-income families could be persuaded to buy homes for which they could not
maintain payments.
Ms Sheila McKechnie, director, said: 'Too many people have already been
encouraged to buy their council houses without realising the full costs of
home ownership.
'Shelter does not want to see families exchanging a secure council tenancy
for a home which later they could lose if they cannot afford a mortgage.'
Sir George insisted that leaflets about the scheme gave enough warnings
about the costs of home ownership, including service charges and interest
rate changes.
He also said that the Department of the Environment had written to banks and
building societies and was confident that they would be prepared and willing
to give advances.
Sir George refused to set any target for judging the success of the
initiative.
</TEXT>
