<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / BR clears way for leasing market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday moved to allay fears over the future of British
Rail's West Coast main line services after Network SouthEast won a year-long
battle for new trains which are to be financed under an innovative Pounds
150m leasing deal.
The deal ends speculation over how BR would use a special leasing concession
announced in last year's Autumn Statement, and will benefit up to 125,000
London commuters. It opens the way for the creation of a leasing market for
rolling stock and also safeguards for a year the jobs of more than 1,000
workers at ABB Transportation's York works, where the new trains will be
built.
InterCity's West Coast main line had been vying with Network SouthEast for
new trains, but BR has decided to use the concession to lease 41 new
four-coach Networker Express trains for Great Northern and Kent Coast
services. Existing Great Northern trains will be switched to the London,
Tilbury &amp; Southend line.
The announcement was criticised by opposition parties. Mr Nick Harvey,
Liberal Democrat transport spokesman, welcomed the investment in Network
SouthEast but said the future of the West Coast main line was now in
question.
Mr Roger Freeman, minister for public transport, said BR's decision did not
reflect any doubts over the importance of the West Coat line. He said he was
prepared to consider subsidising services on the line - even after it is
franchised in 1995 or 1996 - as part of rail privatisation.
He also stressed that the West Coast line's rolling stock would be replaced.
He said the Department of Transport and the Treasury wanted to discuss with
GEC Alsthom, the engineering group, its 'interesting new ideas' on leasing.
The Anglo-French group's bid to build 11 InterCity 225 trains had been
judged too expensive.
</TEXT>
