<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / First estate agent fined over house description
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST estate agent to be prosecuted under the Property Misdescriptions
Act (1991) was fined Pounds 500 and ordered to pay costs of Pounds 570 by
magistrates in Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, yesterday. The act is aimed at
eliminating misleading descriptions of properties.
Mr Ian Sinclair, a chartered surveyor who runs his own estate agency in the
Great Yarmouth area, had failed for five days to amend a newspaper
advertisement and a captioned photograph in his office window to say that
the asking price of a house in Gorleston had risen from Pounds 22,500 to
Pounds 25,000.
A member of the public interested in the property found that the price did
not tally with the advertisement and alerted the local trading standards
department which brought the prosecution.
Mr Sinclair pleaded guilty and elected not to be tried at a crown court. He
said the offence had happened through an administrative error because a new
member of staff had failed to alter the details of the sale.
The magistrates court has the power to impose a maximum fine of Pounds
5,000. After the hearing Mr Sinclair said: 'I am obviously very
disappointed. The fine is not punitive but it is not token either. I had
made a mistake and felt that I should have merely been cautioned.'
Mr Malcolm Patridge, Mr Sinclair's solicitor, said: 'The fine was much
higher than I expected but we will not be appealing.'
Mr Steve Holland, prosecuting solicitor, said he felt vindicated in bringing
the prosecution. 'There has been a substantial fine and I have been awarded
all my costs.'
</TEXT>
