<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / Kuwait ministers set for tax talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KUWAITI finance and oil ministers plan to meet the government to discuss the
Pounds 600m in tax which Kuwait may owe on its investment in British
Petroleum shares.
'I understand they are due over here soon,' said a senior Kuwaiti adviser.
The Financial Times recently reported that Kuwait may have abused its
sovereign immunity from taxation in relation to its purchase in the late
1980s of a stake close to 22 per cent in BP.
It has received more than Pounds 600m in tax refunds on income from the
shares to which it may not have been entitled because the shares were
purchased by the Kuwait Petroleum Corporation and were not a direct
investment of Kuwait, as originally claimed.
The adviser said that it would be unwise for the UK to press for repayment
of the Pounds 600m, because UK exports to Kuwait, especially defence
contracts, could be jeopardised. He said it would be better for the two
countries to come to a 'mutual understanding'.
However, the UK government said there was no possibility of the Inland
Revenue ceasing its investigation of the tax. It added: 'There is no way the
Treasury or Foreign Office can intervene in an investigation of this kind.'
</TEXT>
