<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / Major's press secretary to leave
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR, the prime minister, yesterday signalled a fresh attempt to
rebuild the government's battered public image by appointing a senior
diplomat to replace his outgoing press secretary.
Mr Major said that Mr Gus O'Donnell, his press secretary for four years,
would be replaced in January by Mr Christopher Meyer, Britain's deputy
ambassador in Washington.
Mr O'Donnell, a career economist, is leaving to take up a senior Treasury
post. He is thought to have been seeking an opportunity to return to the
Treasury where he used to work, partly to avoid becoming too closely
identified with the prime minister and the Conservative party.
Mr Meyer, a highly respected diplomat who was head of the Foreign Office
press office from 1984 to 1989, has been deputy head of mission in
Washington since last year.
The prime minister said he was 'very sad' about the departure of Mr
O'Donnell who had done 'a difficult job with great skill and good humour'.
But the appointment was welcomed by rightwingers, many of whom believe Mr
O'Donnell bears some of the blame for the government's presentational
difficulties over the last year.
One senior backbencher said: 'There has been considerable criticism about
the prime minister's private office, and many of us have been looking for
changes.'
Another blamed Mr O'Donnell for remarks attributed to the prime minister in
which rightwing backbenchers were dismissed as 'barmy'. He said the change
could 'only be an improvement'.
Downing Street denied suggestions that Mr O'Donnell had been forced out to
appease the right. He is to become head of the Treasury monetary group,
which advises on interest rates and exchange rate policy.
Mr O'Donnell was working on monetary aggregates at the Treasury when he was
promoted to press secretary by Lord Lawson, the then chancellor. He remained
in the job when Mr Major became chancellor in 1989, and moved with him to 10
Downing Street.
Mr O'Donnell has told friends that he has 'bitter-sweet' feelings about
leaving Number 10, but is pleased to be returning to a 'fun' job at the
Treasury.
Mr Meyer, a fluent Russian speaker and expert on Russian politics, is
described by colleagues as an intelligent high flier destined for the top of
diplomatic service.
Mr Major said that Mr Meyer's 'fine record' in Washington and his experience
in the Foreign Office press office would 'stand him in good stead for this
challenge'.
Like Mr O'Donnell, Mr Meyer will be able to indulge the prime minister's
love of sport. He plays tennis and squash, and is a supporter of Brighton
and Hove Albion Football Club.
</TEXT>
