FT  14 OCT 93 / UN renews Haiti sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council last night ordered a renewal of sanctions against
Haiti unless the military junta complies with its agreement to permit the
deployment of a UN peace mission leading to the return to office of exiled
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
An oil embargo and freeze of Haiti's assets abroad will go into effect on
Monday if General Raul Cedras, the military chief, fails to step down
tomorrow in accordance with the agreement, which also provides for UN troops
to land.
A shipload of US and Canadian soldiers assigned to retrain the military and
police was prevented from disembarking on Monday by unruly Haitian
demonstrators believed to be acting with the military's encouragement.
The Security Council's mandatory resolution, adopted unanimously, responded
to a request by the US and a written recommendation by Mr Boutros Boutros
Ghali, UN secretary general. He reported 'serious and consistent
non-compliance' with the agreement brokered by his special envoy, Mr Dante
Caputo, a former Argentine foreign minister, and a repeated 'lack of will'
by the military to facilitate UN operations.
