<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / World Trade News: Europeans warned about 'Apocalypse soon'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN APOCALYPTIC future for European culture was painted by EC film producers
yesterday, if the cinema and audiovisual sectors are included in the Uruguay
Round of Gatt.
Figures from Europe's cinema industry lobbied the European Commission
yesterday to get the sector taken out of the Round, warning that unless it
is 'Europe will become a Third World continent,' in the words of Mr Wim
Wenders, the German film director.
The Commission says it is fighting for 'cultural specificity' for the films
and broacasting sector, allowing some protection and continuing subsidy.
France, with backing from other member states such as Spain wants a
'cultural exception' exempting cinema altogether.
Prospects last night brightened for France as the US and EC appeared to make
headway in Gatt talks in Brussels towards a compromise on trade in
audio-visual services.
Neither Sir Leon Brittan, EC chief trade negotiator, nor Mr Mickey Kantor,
US trade representative, would give details, but acknowledged progress had
been made on how to address problems in the sector.
EC negotiators had until recently sought in vain to exclude audio-visual
services from the Uruguay Round, but it now appears the EC is proposing the
sector should remain in the Round, but with the focus on abolition of EC
quota restrictions on imported films and television programmes.
This would allow European governments to continue subsidising entertainment
industries.
A range of mostly French industry groups argued yesterday that Europe would
be swamped by Hollywood in a Gatt-regulated open 'culture market'. They
pointed out that US film export revenues rose from Dollars 750m (Pounds
490m) in 1980 to Dollars 5.5bn last year, and that Dollars 3.7bn of 1992
sales were in Europe.
EC attempts to reserve most screening time on television to European work
has not blunted US penetration of the EC market, they said, contrary to US
claims that this was an illegal quota system.
Mr Wenders said that the audiovisual industry would be the biggest on the
planet in the next century. Europe had to decide whether its still modest
share would continue to exist or not, before the Uruguay Round mid-December
deadline. He said: 'To have a market dominated by American imagery means not
only domination by American values and American ideas, but that other
(EC-made) products would disappear,' because of concomitant US domination of
advertising.
</TEXT>
