<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / Israel and PLO set out peace timetable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE and MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TABA, CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL and the Palestine Liberation Organisation yesterday began two months
of detailed negotiations in Cairo and Egypt's Red Sea resort of Taba to
implement their outline peace agreement.
In Taba, where Israeli and Palestinian security and military officials, once
bitter enemies, are meeting to prepare a protocol for Israeli military
withdrawal from the Gaza Strip and West Bank town of Jericho from December
13, the opening day of talks was marred when the Israeli delegation vetoed
three Palestinian delegates.
Israeli officials refused to sit across the table from Mr Amin al-Hindi, PLO
security chief, whom Israeli newspapers and security officials have accused
of helping to plan the massacre of Israelis at the 1972 Munich Olympic
games.
An Israeli foreign ministry official said: 'Munich was one of the greatest
traumas for Jews. We are prepared to make some compromises with Palestinians
but there is a limit.'
Two other delegates were vetoed because they live in Jerusalem, the most
sensitive issue between Israel and the PLO in future talks over territorial
jurisdiction. The three delegates were swiftly replaced by others in the
Palestinian party.
Both sides sought to play down the incident. Mr Nabil Shaath, head of the
PLO delegation, said: 'Nobody was blacklisted, nobody was white-listed ..we
have no problem about composition of the delegation.'
In a joint Israeli-PLO statement, Mr Shaath and Major-General Amnon Shahak,
head of the Israeli delegation, stressed the talks had been 'cordial and
constructive'.
The two sides agreed to set up two working groups to divide security from
civilian issues and to make the release of Palestinian prisoners held in
Israeli jails a 'priority matter'.
The two sub-committees will also focus on the territorial delimitation of
the Jericho area and the transfer of powers from the Israeli military-run
administration to a Palestinian interim authority.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, speaking to Israel Radio during a
visit to China, said the outcome of the Taba talks would be a test for
extending self-rule to other Palestinian areas captured by the Jewish state
in the 1967 war. 'Without meaningful progress in the committee to advance
Gaza-Jericho, all the rest will be simply marginal and secondary,' he said.
In separate talks in Cairo, the two sides set a tight timetable for further
detailed negotiations and established two additional committees on economic
and regional co-operation.
Mr Shimon Peres, Israeli foreign minister, wrapping up the first one-day
meeting of a joint PLO-Israeli liaison committee, said in Cairo: 'We shall
make a supreme effort to meet the time (for withdrawal) and if possible,
attempt to do so earlier'.
Both Mr Peres and Mr Mahmoud Abbas, (Abu Mazen), who headed the PLO
delegation, emphasised the 'positive' spirit of the talks, meeting privately
before the inaugural two-hour session of the liaison committee.
At both the Taba and Cairo meetings, sharp-suited Israeli and Palestinian
security agents milled side by side, stony faced, in the corridors of the
international hotels hosting the talks in what experts said was one of the
first public demonstrations of Israeli-Palestinian security co-operation.
</TEXT>
