<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / Polls show people losing faith in leading German political
parties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's leading political parties have all lost substantial support in the
opinion polls over the past two months, with a significant rise in the
popularity of all the fringe protest groups, writes Quentin Peel. The
Christian Democratic Union, and its Bavarian sister party, the Christian
Social Union, would get only 30.9 per cent support if there were an election
this week, according to the latest poll by the Allensbach Institute. At the
last general election in December, 1990, the parties won 43.8 per cent. The
Social Democrats are down to 35.4 per cent, compared with 38.2 per cent in
the west and 34.8 per cent in the east. The principal beneficiaries have
been the Greens, up to 12.1 per cent, and the far right Republicans, up to
5.6 per cent, enough to gain them seats in the Bundestag.
</TEXT>
