<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / US investors set to take big stake in Lloyd's agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of US financial institutions is poised to acquire a substantial
stake in the Merrett underwriting agency in a significant innovation for the
Lloyd's insurance market.
The Merrett group said yesterday it had approached Lloyd's with an outline
plan to transfer its underwriting business to a new agency, in which JP
Morgan, the investment bank, Marsh &amp; McLennan Risk Capital, a subsidiary of
Marsh &amp; McLennan, the world's biggest insurance broker, Merrett employees
and an unnamed US insurance company would own stakes.
It is envisaged that the agency would underwrite business for a subsidiary
of the same US insurance company, which would operate alongside Merrett's
insurance syndicates on a so-called 'consortium' basis.
Together, the insurance company and the syndicates would aim to maintain
Merrett's insurance business at its existing levels.
The move follows a sharp contraction in the capital base of the Merrett
syndicates after the desertion this year of many Names, the individuals
whose assets traditionally support Lloyd's.
Mr Stephen Merrett, chairman of the Merrett group, has reduced his role in
the agency after pressure from Names, and resigned as deputy chairman of
Lloyd's last month.
Mr Stephen Cane, managing director of the Merrett Group, said the new
investors would 'probably' have a majority of the new agency. He insisted
that the Merrett Group did not want to leave Lloyd's, but conceded that
'this is a significant departure for a typical Lloyd's underwriting
operation'.
The insurance company is a 'substantial and significant' US group. It could
provide about a quarter of the Merrett agencies' capacity next year, Mr Cane
said. More than three quarters of the business underwritten by Merrett
syndicates comes from the US.
Lloyd's said yesterday that it was 'considering proposals carefully. In so
far as they require consent and approval from Lloyd's we shall be
approaching consideration of these (matters) from the standpoint of the
interests of Names on Merrett syndicates, whose interests are also
recognised by the Merrett Group'.
Although overseas interests have never before held control of a Lloyd's
managing agency, it is understood that there is nothing in the regulatory
framework to prohibit such a move.
Marsh and Morgan agreed this year to form a new Bermuda-based company to
reinsure business accepted by the Merrett syndicates. But the sudden decline
in the fortunes of the Merrett Group this year had jeopardised the success
of that plan.
The group hopes to conclude talks on the new arrangements by the end of the
month.
</TEXT>
