<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (32): A helping hand from shared ideas / A look
at an initiative that has brought together companies from three European
countries to learn from each other's experiences - Supporting exports, The
ICDP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ADVENT of the European Single Market has meant that companies large and
small are increasingly being cajoled to adopt an 'export-or-die' approach to
their business.
But, for the small or medium-sized business with limited management
resources and little experience outside its traditional home market, the
effort needed to break into an export market can be a bewildering and even
traumatic experience.
It was with such companies in mind that an initiative was taken several
years ago by the Irish Productivity Centre (IPC) - an organisation jointly
funded by the Irish Business and Employers' Confederation and the Irish
Congress of Trade Unions - to bring together a group of small but expanding
companies, from different countries and business cultures, in order that
they might learn and swap experiences.
Called the International Company Development Programme (ICDP), Ireland,
Denmark and the Netherlands each selected six companies to participate in an
18-month programme of seminars and workshops. The Dutch Institute for Small
and Medium Craft Businesses (CIMK) and the Jutland Institute of Technology
co-ordinated the programme with the IPC.
'The focus of the programme was on management development, to develop a team
rather than individuals,' says Tom McGuinness of the IPC. 'The idea was that
the participating companies would develop a strategic development plan to
make them more competitive and give them greater export potential'.
The first programme ran from 1989 to 1990, and for some companies it meant
that up to 20 per cent of management effort was taken up over this period in
attending and preparing for the seminars and workshops.
'The main problem was the release of people,' Mr McGuinness said. 'There was
always a temptation for production managers not to attend, while the whole
point was precisely to get managers not normally associated with the export
side of the business there and to understand their role as part of a team.'
Most believed, however, that the programme represented management time well
spent. Rob Zaadnoordijk, the sales director of a yacht-building firm Fripol
BV near Amsterdam, said that his company had benefitted from the project.
'We are now working much more intensively on our export business,' he said.
'The EC borders are now open, so our home market is much bigger and there is
much more competition. The really important thing we learned is that we have
to be much more competitive.'
He said the programme made clear that 'it is not enough to say we are
European to be European. Each country has its own culture and own particular
way of doing business'.
Jan Klingeman, managing director of Spijkstaal - a Dutch company with a
Fl30m annual turnover, which manufactures electric vehicles and truck bodies
 -said his five-strong management team used the programme 'to find out how
we can better go about getting foreign customers'. He said that while it has
since taken three years to begin developing the export side of the business,
it was precisely the ICDP programme that made them realise that this time
was needed to prepare the company thoroughly.
'Now we are ready to go looking abroad. We have taken over another company
and largely closed down another arm of the business. That has taken a lot of
time. But the experience of the development programme helped us to plan more
strategically and we are now better prepared to go into the export market'.
The need for preparation was one of the strongest messages to come out of
the programme according to Mr McGuinness. 'Costs associated with exporting
are greater and profit margins are often smaller,' he said.
'Preparation is very important. Many small companies are not prepared
sufficiently and exporting is not necessarily the best approach. If you
cannot service the home market profitably it is unlikely you will have
success in the export market.'
A more ambitious programme undertaken in 1991 involving Ireland, Denmark,
Spain, Portugal and Scotland was run over a period of 13 months instead of
18.
But it was less successful according to Mr McGuinness. 'There is an
exponential rise in difficulties with the number of countries
participating,' he said. Organisation was more complex and participants did
not interact as well, tending to stay within their own language groups, he
added.
Nevertheless participants reacted positively. 'It succeeded in getting
everybody pointing in the same direction. We found we were not unique with
our problems and it led us to take the conscious decision that we should
look at the British Isles as our home market and not just Ireland,' said
Tony Gillespie, marketing manager of Solids Technology, an Irish company
specialising in the separation and treatment of slurry wastes.
'We also spend more time now on strategic thinking. For instance, we have
decided that licensing our technology in the United States rather than
exporting from Ireland is a better option because of exchange rate
uncertainty and because we cannot afford to dedicate the resources that an
export strategy requires,' Mr Gillespie said.
John Harris, production director of Printech, an Irish company producing
computer manuals was enthusiastic about the project. 'It was an excellent
programme. It gave us a platform from which to understand other markets and
cultures and helped us develop our middle management'. Company work
practices had changed as a result, he said with more flexibility and less
demarcation on production lines now than in the past. Printech now generates
10 per cent of its Pounds 20m turnover from exports.
Oddly, neither of the two programmes involved any structured follow-up, a
fact which most companies said would have been helpful. 'There is a wealth
of knowledge out there, but not enough co-operation. The experience gained
is not being fully utilised,' one manager said.
</TEXT>
