<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (31): Cost a crucial component - While British
exporters frequently complain of overcharging, Mushtak Parker finds that
competition on the continent prevents the practice / How to pick a partner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MUSHTAK PARKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For small and medium sized exporters, freight charges can often make or
break a contract. Marginal savings on freight costs can also contribute to
cash flow. In some export markets, such as the oil-rich Gulf the freight
factor is a predominant issue.
'For lighter fuel exports, for instance, on the price per dozen CFR Dubai,
an importer will argue on two or three pence per dozen, saying that his
profit margin is only 2 per cent or so,' says Phillip Ballie, export manager
of Ukexx Ballie which has an annual turnover of Pounds 500,000 and sells
German-made time and light-sensitive printing plates to Africa, the Middle
East and the West Indies.
Since freight costs - especially in landlocked developing countries such as
the CIS - make up almost half export earnings, according to a United Nations
report, managing those costs is crucial to success as an exporter. Small
exporters must decide whether to leave decisions in the hands of their
forwarders or handle the freight buying themselves. Choosing the right
freight forwarder is therefore imperative.
A common complaint of small and medium-sized British exporters is that they
are often overcharged. Some forwarders negotiate discounts with shippers and
neglect to subtract the discount from the cost to exporters.
At 5 per cent, this could well make the difference between winning a
contract and losing it to competitors and often leads to a dispute between
the exporter and the forwarder. Top exporters can always buy the best rates,
but the small exporter has no such buying power and often suffers as a
result.
According to Mr Baillie of Ukexx, primarily a UK-based buying house for a
Nigerian company, the practice of overcharging is rife. 'You could pick up a
phone and speak to half a dozen agents and you will be quoted six different
rates. It is a question of building up a relationship with your agent,' he
says.
'Small exporters do not have the luxury of an in-house freight forwarding
department, which would include a representative of a forwarding firm, which
would charge the company on an agency basis,' Mr Baillie adds.
The British industry's trade body, the British International Freight
Association (Bifa), whose membership comprises some 60 per cent of small and
medium-sized companies, acknowledges that there is a problem but blames the
government at least for contributing to it.
Bifa says that little support has come from government for any form of
statutory regulation, whether through the bonding or licensing of
forwarders. Further, underwriters have been reluctant to accept the
perceived risks the forwarder is exposed to, with the result that freight
forwarding has become a free for all.
Some British exporters and freight forwarders rue the fact that the Office
of Fair Trading has done away with the standard charges and itemised tariffs
on the grounds that this represented a cartel with price-fixing.
'Because of the nature of how UK Plc operates - under market principles -
the ethos is: 'Let the Buyer (of services) Beware'. Unless he is familiar
with the market and understands how it works, he is vulnerable,' says Bifa's
divisional manager Colin Beaumont.
'The market ethic is: 'You charge what you can get away with'. The problem
is a symptom of market economics and is having a detrimental effect on small
business.'
Attempts are being made to halt the practice of overcharging. Through its
'New Exporter Initiative', introduced three years ago, Bifa introduced new
exporters to a range of freight companies. They were advised as to what
questions exporters should ask their freight forwarders, what priorities
should be outlined and what freight costs exporters were likely to come up
against.
Exporters are given a list of accredited members, says Mr Beaumont, and the
association trains staff of member companies and urges any exporter who has
a complaint against a forwarder who is a member of Bifa to report it.
But Bifa itself has come in for criticism from its members. 'A great deal
more could have been done in the past to strengthen the image of freight
forwarders,' says Mike Guinn, a regional director with the Swiss-based
Kuehne &amp; Nagel (K&amp;N) and former chairman of the Bristol-based M&amp;M Services,
which K&amp;N bought from the receivers earlier this year. 'Minimum standards
and rates should have been introduced from the start. The industry had its
own salvation in its hands. It has failed itself.'
Mr Guinn concedes, however, that regulations concerning the licensing of
freight companies in the UK are not as tough as those in some other EC
countries.
Across the channel, overcharging is almost non-existent because of the
intense competition in the sector. Jean Claude de Gassart, general manager
of the Federation Francaise des Organisateurs Commissionaires de Transport
(FFOCT), says few complaints are made against its 2,200-strong members.
'Freight forwarding services must be paid for. If they are too expensive,
then an exporter will find another freight company. There is sufficient
competition to find the right forwarder at the right price,' he says.
Freight officials in the Netherlands maintain that competition is so severe
that overcharging is not possible. 'Exporters and importers will always
complain against charges,' says Han Van Os, general manager of the
Netherlands Association for Forwarding &amp; Logistics.
'Profit margins in the freight transport sector are marginal. But a freight
company has to make a profit in order to survive. Dutch law allows exporters
to do their own forwarding. If they are concerned about the rates then they
can do it themselves for less,' he says.
Licensing requirements in Britain differ greatly from those in leading
countries on the continent. FFOCT's Mr De Gassart is concerned that the
opening of the EC's internal frontiers has created an uneven playing field
in the freight transport sector and wants to see a uniform set of EC
regulations governing the industry in all member states.
French forwarders are wary of differences in licensing regulations in
developing EC states, which are deemed lax and which supposedly give firms
from those countries a competitive edge. They also worry about competition
from emerging eastern European forwarders and those from the Maghreb
countries.
French freight industry licensing criteria requires a company to have a
manager with at least 10 year's experience and a diploma in general
education, a clean record as far as fraud and tax irregularities are
concerned and certain capital provisions.
The regulations governing the licence to trade in Germany vary depending on
what type of freight company is being set up, says Mr Reinhardt Lankes of
the Bundesverband Spedition Lageri EV (BSL). Because of the strict licensing
scheme in operation, the BSL - which has 5,000 members across the freight
transport sector - does not have membership criteria or conditions other
than the licence itself. Mr Lankes claims that the freight sector is well
regulated and problems of overcharging are not common.
What then is the advice to exporters when choosing a freight forwarder?
Most exporters choose a freight forwarder because they either know one or
have been recommended one. 'The important thing is that you trust your agent
at the end of the day. I am prepared to pay for a good service. After all
the agent takes care of all the documentation and certificates of origin,'
says Mr Ballie of Ukexx.
Bifa's Mr Beaumont believes that exporters must look around the market. They
must understand what their own requirements are and should contact the
association that could then help them through outlets such as exports clubs
and one stop shops.
'We do feed all these networks to try to advise exporters what they need.
People tend not to get advice until they have a problem,' says Mr Beaumont.
Freight forwarders such as Mr Guinn of K&amp;N, on the other hand, urge
exporters to try to find companies that give a personal service and those
with a good local office. 'It is all about people. There are about 10 top
freight forwarders in the EC and you, as an exporter, should find one you
will be comfortable with.'
Exporters want to cut costs and reduce the number of contractors in the
supply chain. David Grant, marketing director of P&amp;O Containers Europe,
whose clients include small, medium and large exporters, says the freight
majors such as P&amp;O guarantee quality and service standards.
He advises export firms to do their homework and to look at all the options,
door-to-door type of price (inland costs, fixed rate costs, warehouse and
distribution costs), efficiency and the level of service offered.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
