<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (30): Small is still beautiful - Mushtak Parker
finds that, despite a wave of mergers and acquisitions, there will always be
a demand for small and medium-sized operators / Freight forwarders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MUSHTAK PARKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE acquisition of Bristol-based freight forwarder M&amp;M Services from the
receivers last July by the Swiss-based freight giant Kuehne &amp; Nagel (K&amp;N)
reflects the uncertainty independent and small freight companies are facing.
The feeling among independent operators is that as the recession in the
European Community continues to bite, small and medium-sized freight
forwarders will find it hard to survive. M&amp;M Services, with an annual
turnover of about Dollars 8m, was once the Rolls Royce of the freight
forwarding industry, but with profit margins and commissions reduced, it
became impossible to compete with the pricing power of the freight majors.
According to a former M&amp;M Services chairman Mike Guinn, now a regional
director with K&amp;N, losses sustained by the independents and small freight
companies through mergers of bankruptcies is a worldwide problem. 'We could
not survive because our ability to give the level required by the industry
was not sustainable,' he says. 'Investment in tracking services and
computerisation requires a lot of money which only the majors can afford.
Ours was a personal service and not one dictated by computers.'
A mixture of mergers and acquisitions, joint ventures, cross-border
alliances, management buy-outs or simply bankruptcy has swept across the
industry in the past year.
A survey by Dutch management consultancy Van der Geer and Van Hasenbroek
carried out earlier this year found that in the five years from 1988, some
200 acquisitions took place in the Dutch road haulage sector alone. British
and US firms accounted for a third of the takeovers. In France, bankruptcies
among road hauliers during last year increased by 2.5 per cent on the
previous year.
Some independents such as Communication Rapide Inter-Enterprises (CRIE), the
French integrator in the international parcels express sector, whose clients
include Peugeot, Renault, Barclays Bank and Digital, are maintaining market
share by offering a flexible service. CRIE claims a 10 per cent share of the
international express market from France.
With the European freight distribution market exceeding Ecu160bn (Pounds
122bn), the stakes are high. Some cross-border mergers and strategic
alliances have been spurred by the perceived opportunities in the Single
Market.
But most multinationals, while cutting costs, are acquiring companies in
target markets, then consolidating to meet local freight transport needs.
Sometimes the strategy does not work, but the effect is felt across the
sector. US express parcels company Federal Express (FedEx) made heavy losses
attempting to establish itself in the UK, and was forced to pull out.
The consensus is, however, that small and medium-sized freight forwarders
have a role to play. 'There will always be a need for small freight
companies,' says Colin Beaumont, divisional manager of the British
International Freight Association, whose membership comprises 60 per cent
small and medium-sized companies. 'From time to time you will have mergers
and acquisitions and this is a reasonably healthy process.
'It is not a trend. It has happened all the time. I would say that there
have not been more bankruptcies and takeovers during the recession that in
normal operating times. Freight forwarding is a fragmented and a niche
market business,' Mr Beaumont says.
At the other end of the industry, alignment, mergers and contractions are
needed to maintain margins or to stay in business. Analysts do not see this
changing. David Grant, marketing director of P&amp;O containers Europe, stresses
that the big companies are not getting bigger. 'Companies are helping each
other out and the trend is no different from any other business or sector.
'Joint ventures and other alliances offer opportunities to reduce costs.
Smaller operators will have to look at their niche markets and work with
bigger companies to capitalise in terms of efficiencies and investment
opportunities into computer systems and EDI (Electronic Data Interchange)
networks,' Mr Grant says.
The leading freight operators claim that they are not making big profits,
but rationalisation does mean better rates, services and greater efficiency.
Mr Grant acknowledges that the large operators do have a responsibility to
the industry and partnership is definitely a trend but he remains optimistic
about prospects for forwarders. 'The recession offers opportunities as well.
The international movement of goods does not necessarily go down,' he says.
But Mr Guinn says he would not even consider starting a venture such as M&amp;M
Services now. 'We've been fortunate, despite the receivership. At K&amp;N there
are the inevitable changes and these have been fairly painless. The
acquisition has gone as well as one could have hoped for. In the
circumstances this was the best deal for M&amp;M Services creditors, customers
and employees.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4731 Freight Transportation Arrangement.
</IN>
