<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (27): Little cause for celebration - Recession
and dramatic changes in European exchange rates are not helping France's
renowned champagne house / Company profile of Moet-et-Chandon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR decades the champagnes from the vineyards around the cities of Reims and
Epernay in eastern France have been among the most profitable and
prestigious areas of French exports.
One of the chief catalysts of champagne's export success has been
Moet-et-Chandon, the grand old Epernay champagne house that now belongs to
LVMH, the powerful luxury goods group. Moet, which was founded in 1743, has
devoted years to establishing its brand as the world's best-selling
champagne.
Moet-et-Chandon, like the rest of the champagne industry, has had a tough
time in recent months, not least because of the effect of the dramatic
changes in European exchange rates on its export sales. The company has had
not only to grapple with the effects of the recession on worldwide demand
for champagne, but has also had to revise its pricing policy because of
France's franc fort policy of maintaining a strong franc.
The problems of Moet are illustrative, not only of the particular
difficulties of the champagne trade, but also of the general pressures on
other French exporters since last autumn's currency crisis strengthened the
franc against other currencies.
Exports were, until recently, one of the chief sources of growth for the
French economy. For most of last year French companies were able to
compensate for the low level of domestic demand by winning market share in
other countries. The value of French exports rose by 6.5 per cent in 1992,
according to the economy ministry, and the trading account swung from a
FFr29.6bn deficit into a FFr30.6bn credit.
But last autumn's currency crisis, which strengthened the franc against
other European currencies - notably the lira, peseta and sterling - made
life more difficult for French exporters. Their problems began in the final
quarter of 1992, but intensified early this year. The trading account has
stayed in the black: but only because of a sharp decline in imports.
Champagne, already struggling against the parallel problems of weak demand
and over-production, has been one of the most vulnerable areas of French
industry. Champagne exports peaked at 94.3m bottles in 1989, according to
the Comite Interprofessionel du Vin de Champagne, but then fell steadily to
73.8m bottles in 1992.
The franc's strength after the currency crisis was the final straw for the
industry. Exports levels seemed to rally in the first half of this year -
reaching 25m bottles against 23.6m in the same period of 1992 - but only
because of the steep increase in sales of cheap petits champagnes at the
expense of the established brands.
Moet, which represents around 7 per cent of the total champagne market, has
suffered with the rest of the industry. By the first quarter of this year it
was acutely concerned not only about the low level of sales in
recession-struck France, but also that the strong franc was making its
product seem too expensive in other countries.
LVMH announced in February that it was 'temporarily' cutting the wholesale
price of Moet - and also of Mercier champagne - by 10 per cent in France,
Germany and Switzerland to try to rekindle demand. Under ordinary
circumstances it would almost certainly have cut prices by the same amount
elsewhere in Europe.
But the franc's strength also raised the risk of an influx of parallel
imports of Moet into France and Germany, from countries with weaker
currencies, such as the UK, Spain and Italy. Instead of trimming its prices
in those markets, LVMH was forced to raise them by 5 per cent.
The decision to revise Moet's pricing policy was not taken easily. Moet,
like every other champagne house, was anxious about the effect cutting
prices would have on the prestigious image of its product. It was also
concerned that its wholesale customers in France, Germany and Switzerland
might not pass the reductions on to their retail clients. As a result it
would have reduced its own margins and imperilled the status of its brand
without gaining from higher sales.
Further, the need to raise prices in the UK, Italy and Spain raised the risk
of further depressing sales in those markets. This was one of the factors
that prompted Moet this spring to announce a job-cutting plan which has
brought it into fierce conflict with the trade unions.
In spite of these difficulties Moet has stuck to its new policy. It says
that demand is still weak in most European markets, although it has detected
a slight improvement since the franc's fall following this summer's ERM
crisis. However, there are more encouraging signs in the US as the recession
ends, and in the UK, even after the price rises.
</TEXT>
