<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (24): UK body steps into the breach - The Single
Market Compliance Unit is resolving a large number of complaints while
others may not yet have come to light - Illegal trade barriers / The SMCU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY BUSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH exporters who feel their European sales are being hampered by
illegal trade barriers have a white knight to turn to at the Department of
Trade and Industry.
Any company that believes its products have been rejected by an invidious
application of 'national standards' or some other unfair ploy, can appeal to
the Single Market Compliance Unit (SMCU)*, set up by the department to
resolve difficulties caused by breaches of EC rules.
The unit, created four years ago, has recently been expanded to deal with
increasing numbers of complaints about alleged breaches. Its caseload has
risen from five in 1989 to 19 in 1990, 28 in 1991, 58 in 1992 and to more
than 60 so far this year.
The unit believes many other cases may not yet have come to light. 'The
problems brought to us appear to be fairly typical of those that UK business
faces, although the extent of those problems can be hard to judge,' a
spokesman for SMCU said.
Because exporters often find a way round particular problems and are
reluctant to complain, these problems are not exposed and resolved in the
long term.
Even those companies that do take their troubles to the unit, do not want
publicity. 'Everything we do for the exporter is treated confidentially,'
says the DTI. As a result, SMCU triumphs rarely make the headlines. As the
unit gains experience in tackling certain issues, its success rate is
expanding.
But it recoils at the idea that it might be seen as a 'quick fix' body and
points out that results are rarely swift and cases are seldom clear cut.
Often, the SMCU is seen as a place of last resort. Cases are referred to the
unit by MPs, MEPs, ministers, embassies and trade associations.
When a complaint is taken to the unit, the evidence is assessed and, if the
unit feels a case exists, it calls on other Whitehall departments or British
embassies for the technical and regional expertise needed to confirm whether
a breach has occured. Thereafter a course of action is agreed upon with the
exporter.
Actions open to the unit include taking the matter up with a member state
through Brussels, getting ministers to contact their counterpart in the
member state concerned and asking ambassadors to raise the issue with the
ministry concerned.
If these bilateral approaches fail, a case can be referred to the European
Commission by the complainant, with the SMCU acting in an advisory role. The
Commission may then initiate 'infraction proceedings' but these can take two
or three years to reach a resolution.
Complaints include failure to recognise common standards, refusal to comply
with public procurement rules, an exporter not being given a test date for a
product and delays in receiving the test results.
The question of national standards being used to block trade is particularly
vexing at a time when the Community is moving towards spreading the use of
its own harmonised mark of conformity: CE marking. Any product bearing the
marking will have met criteria laid down by the relevant EC New Approach
Directive - regulations concerning standards for each sector - and will be
acceptable in any country within the EC.
The idea is that national standards must be withdrawn when they conflict
with European standards. This, however, is a minefield when it comes to
compliance and a quarter of the cases the unit has taken on this year
concern standards.
In spite of the increase in complaints, the SMCU says deliberate breaches of
Community law by member states are rarer than is commonly believed.
'Most problems come about through difficulties caused by the very different
systems across the Community,' it says. 'There is little evidence of
deliberate, wide-scale, illegal practice by other member states'
authorities, but problems do occur through different interpretation of the
rules or patchy enforcement.
Although the SMCU has several contacts in other EC countries willing to
assist in resolving difficulties, the only other European country to have a
similar body is Denmark, whose industry ministry has set up what is called
the 'Hoovergang'*.
While SCMU and Hoovergang have met to exchange experiences, their contact is
infrequent because few problems arise between the UK and Denmark.
*Single Market Compliance Unit: 44-(0)71-215-6730; Hoovergang: 45-31-851066
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
