<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (22): More than just a pretty picture - Neil
Buckley discovers that the packaging of products is vital for those who want
to succeed in culturally different markets / Labelling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN KP launches its Branigans thick-cut potato crisps in Spain, the packs
will be without the drawing of Mr Branigan holding a tray of his wares
familiar to devotees of the snack in the UK.
Instead, Spanish snack-munchers will be confronted by a picture of a woman.
The company was worried that cultural differences might mean a picture of a
man engaging in the unmanly pursuit of baking would not go down well in
Spain.
For companies exporting consumer goods into foreign markets, the labelling
and packaging to be used is a crucial consideration. A simple oversight -
such as failing to take account of cultural differences - could prove costly
and difficult to rectify later.
Getting the packaging right, on the other hand, can bring rich rewards.
Galbani, the Italian cheese producer, replaced 10 different packaging
designs across Europe in 1991 with a standard one depicting the Tuscan
landscape, a Gingham table cloth and appetising dishes for each cheese.
Without any advertising, sales increased 22 per cent in the UK, 33 per cent
in Germany and 50 per cent in France within six months.
Broadly, exporters face two types of problems when labelling products for
foreign customers. Firstly, they must ensure labels comply with legislation
in the target market. Secondly, they must make choices about how to present
a product, bearing in mind cultural, historical and linguistic differences.
Labelling legislation can be complex. EC directive 79/112 covering the
labelling of foodstuffs runs to 10 pages. While EC harmonisation at least
means that a company which meets all the requirements on naming,
ingredients, quantity, use-by dates and so on in one Community country
should do so in another, there are still pitfalls.
The directive says, for example, that food producers must display
information about their products in a language easily understood by
customers in the local market.
That means manufacturers must either supply goods with labels printed in the
appropriate language, apply stickers in the appropriate language to the
original packaging, or distribute explanatory leaflets along with the
foodstuffs.
Exporters to new markets must check carefully the labelling requirements
with the authorities in that country.
Once the legal requirements have been met, companies must decide whether to
use the same labelling as they do in their home market, or to adapt it for
overseas markets.
'When you're going into a market where you have not been before, the major
priority is getting to know your audience, and finding out about the
cultural differences,' says Jan Marshall of Coley Porter Bell, the London
design consultancy.
There are obvious advantages in harmonising labelling across foreign
markets. It allows centralised marketing, saving money on advertising and
design, and keeps open the possibility of advertising via cross-border media
such as satellite television.
It also allows for a more cohesive and effective brand strategy. Devising a
strong image for a brand can actually help it to cross borders and transcend
language barriers.
There can, however, be problems with such an approach. It may be difficult
to use the same product name as some names may lose their impact in
different markets.
Moreover, names may translate badly. Marketing the anti-perspirant Body Mist
might be difficult in Germany, where 'mist' means manure or dung.
Where different names for the same product exist in different markets,
harmonising them can be difficult. But it can be done.
Mars, the US-owned food manufacturer, did it successfully with its Snickers
bar, previously known in the UK as Marathon. The change was heralded well in
advance of its introduction, with a 'flash' on the pack warning the product
was 'soon to be called Snickers'. After the name change, the flash changed
to 'formerly known as Marathon'.
Mars was helped by a strong packaging design that was the same everywhere
despite the different name.
Sometimes, manufacturers decide not to change different brand names that are
well-established in different countries, but continue to capitalise on the
customer loyalty within each country. A good example is Unilever, which
decided to retain the existing names of its main laundry detergent, known
variously as All, Omo, Persil, Presto, Skip and Via.
But it did adopt a more harmonised approach to packaging, using similar
visual devices, typography and colours, to ensure that Persil buyers from
the UK would recognise a packet of Omo as the same product if they were
confronted with it overseas.
Harmonising packaging design, however, can be difficult. Colours, for
example, are used differently in different countries. In Germany, it is
quite normal to market products for babies in bold, bright colours. In the
UK, pastel shades are more acceptable.
Pictures and images can also create problems. Nudity or semi-nudity, while
acceptable in countries such as France, is clearly out in Muslim countries.
Even if the basic design and lettering of a label is the same, companies may
decided to carry a different message or slogan on the label in different
countries.
Although Unilever launched its new Sun Progress dishwasher powder in a
standard packaging design, research in France, Germany, Italy and the UK
revealed widely differing consumer priorities.
The result was that when Sun Progress was introduced into Germany in 1990,
the packaging message stressed the product's environmental credentials. When
it was launched later in the UK, the message emphasised its value for money
and the fact that it would not cause damage to fine china.
For exporters to be successful in foreign markets, having the right product
is not enough. Just as important is presenting it the right way.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
