<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (23): Changing attitudes - Jeremy Miles believes
that, despite new EC directives resistance to pan-European buying will
continue - Procurement / Profile of Quasar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JEREMY MILES is a strong supporter of the European Commission's efforts to
open up the public procurement market. But he is also extremely thankful for
the fact that Quasar Microwave Technology, the company of which he is
chairman, operates in a market where there are no obvious 'national
champions'.
Quasar makes wave guides, hollow metal conductors which carry microwave
signals to and from radar and telecommunications antennae. It faces
competition from manufacturers in Italy, Germany and France, as well as from
the US, but the sector is too specialised to prompt governments to defend
large national suppliers.
Quasar, which is based in Heathfield, near Exeter, Devon, has turnover of
Pounds 3m and a workforce of 100 people. Established in 1985, it made some
over-ambitious acquisitions, says Mr Miles. He joined the company 18 months
ago at the request of the company's institutional investors to help sort out
its problems.
Europe can no longer afford to have one and sometimes even two or three
domestic champions in each member state, particularly in high technology
areas, he says. 'Deals will continue to be done on the golf course but the
public procurement directives represent an attempt to coerce the member
states to stop thinking of their public authorities and their utilities as
political tools.'
Quasar sells 60 per cent of its turnover in continental Europe either
directly to public authorities and utilities or to the main contractors
involved in projects. Mr Miles calculates that his company manages to
convert half of what he calls 'qualified enquiries' into firm orders.
In spite of his welcome for the EC directives, Mr Miles believes that it
will take some time before ingrained attitudes are changed. 'New generations
will grow up to regard pan-European buying as utterly normal but for the
time being there will be resistance,' he says.
In addition, many suppliers may be reluctant to attempt to break into new
markets because they have become so used to them being closed to foreign
manufacturers. 'Most of us have had to husband our resources and look for
softer targets. But we have to break the mould.'
The new timetables for publishing details of tenders are of symbolic rather
than practical significance, he believes. By the time a tender appears in
the Official Journal it is probably already too late, he says. Suppliers
will only win new business if they get to know their customers and their
likely requirements well in advance.
And even then a purchaser is unlikely to entrust an order for important
equipment to an unknown supplier. Initial orders are likely to be small
until the supplier has proved it can deliver a reliable product.
</TEXT>
