<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (21): Numbers crunch - Wage costs are important,
but productivity differences mean their net effect on competitiveness is
hard to calculate / Labour costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR costs play a large part in the debate about export competitiveness
because they are easy to identify, more variable than some other costs and
the subject of understandable political excitement.
Labour cost differences are, of course, important, but they also need to be
kept in perspective. In the high technology industries which are coming
increasingly to dominate international trade they often make up only a small
proportion of total costs.
In the UK computer industry, for example, total wage costs, including
national insurance contributions, represent only 15 per cent of production
costs. In electronics they represent 34 per cent and in aerospace 33 per
cent.
Manual workers wages (both skilled and unskilled) account for only 4 per
cent of production costs in computers, 13 per cent in electronics, and 23
per cent in aerospace.
Hugh Stirk, head of personnel at Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch consumer goods
company, also points out that in the consumer sector the freedom to choose
where to site an export base is constrained by the need to be physically
close to consumers.
Nonetheless, there is a growing awareness that differences in wage, and
especially non-wage, labour costs between countries can affect
competitiveness. As Mr Stirk says, if it costs twice as much to employ a
senior manager in Germany as in Britain, it will eventually have some
effect.
Employers' non-wage labour costs usually cover government social security
levies plus, in some countries, pension and health payments for employees.
Average figures comparing the US, Japan and the European Community show that
in EC countries non-wage labour costs are about 24 per cent of total labour
costs, only just ahead of the 23 per cent in the US, but comfortably ahead
of Japan where they are 13 per cent.
Those averages disguise huge differences between companies and countries.
Within the EC, for example, Denmark has average non-wage labour costs of
only 3 per cent while France, Italy, Belgium, Germany and the Netherlands
are all above 30 per cent.
And even within one country, such as the United States, there can be huge
differences in labour costs, depending on the sort of healthcare that
employers provide.
Combining both wage costs and non-wage costs, plus various other fringe
benefits, the latest Economist Intelligence Unit survey of hourly labour
costs in the manufacturing industry found that Germany was at the top of the
list on Dollars 25.34, and comfortably well ahead of Switzerland on Dollars
22.48.
They lead a high labour cost country list which includes Norway, Belgium,
the Netherlands, Denmark, Sweden and Austria.
Japan comes in just above Austria towards the bottom of the predominantly
European list on Dollars 19.05. America heads a medium labour cost list with
Dollars 16.58 coming ahead of France, Italy, Finland, the UK, Ireland and
Spain. Those on the low labour cost list comprise Greece on Dollars 6.29 and
Portugal on Dollars 4.69, which is about one-sixth the German level.
Currency fluctuations can, of course, make an enormous difference. The
reason why the average EC hourly rate fell below Japan for the first time
ever this year is due to the rise of the yen. Similarly, the gap between the
US and Europe has narrowed largely because of the strength of the dollar.
Even more important, bald hourly labour cost figures take no account of
differences in productivity. The important factor for employers is not the
level of labour costs as such (and still less the non-wage cost element) but
cost relative to the value-added generated by the labour that they employ.
As the European Commission's report Employment In Europe 1993 states:
'Whatever the level of labour costs, if the contribution of a worker to
value-added is sufficiently high, then it will be profitable to employ him
or her.'
Large differences in labour costs between countries are usually balanced by
equally large variations in the level of productivity.
According to the European Commission, for example, there are only two
European Community countries - Germany and Denmark - where the level of
productivity is substantially below the relative level of labour costs.
On the other hand in four countries - the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Ireland
and Portugal - the average labour costs are significantly lower than the
relative level of productivity, which would imply low unit labour costs.
However, absolute levels of manufacturing unit labour costs are difficult to
calculate and big differences exist between the figures quoted.
The latest calculations from the Trades Union Congress, based on figures
from the US Department of Labour and the OECD, find unit labour costs in the
US, Japan and Germany, to be, respectively, only 66 per cent, 65 per cent
and 71 per cent of the UK level.
When thinking about labour costs businesses need to take into account not
only currencies and productivity but also the trends in cost differentials.
As the London Economics consultancy has pointed out a substantial
convergence of wages has taken place in the EC over the past 20 years.
Spanish wages in 1970 were 29 per cent of those in Germany; in 1990 they had
risen to 66 per cent. Italian wages in 1970 were 42 per cent of those in
Germany; by 1990 they had risen to 71 per cent. So a decision based on the
relative wage costs in 1970 might have looked very different had 1990
relative wage costs been taken into account.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
