<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (20): Prising open the public sector / A look at
new rules designed to stop governments, local authorities and public
utilities from shutting out foreign suppliers - Procurement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GERMAN company supplies chairs to Danish kindergartens. A French company
provides road sweeping services to English local authorities. A British
manufacturer bids to supply mail sacks to the German Post Office.
Public sector contracts, traditionally closed to foreign suppliers, are
slowly being opened up. A market worth Pounds 500m a year and equivalent to
about 15 per cent of the European Community's gross domestic product is
being weaned off national preferences.
There is still a long way to go. Public officials spending taxpayers' money
have been slow to perceive the benefits of buying in a pan-European market.
But a raft of new EC legislation is helping shift entrenched attitudes.
Six directives have been promulgated over the past five years to open up
public procurement markets. The aim is to ensure that the Single Market
takes effect in the public sector by preventing governments, local
authorities and water, transport and power companies from discriminating
against foreign suppliers.
The cornerstone of the new regime is a requirement that public authorities
publish the details of their larger contracts in the EC's Official Journal
(the S series).* The same information is also available in electronic form
through Tenders Electronic Daily, an EC database.
In 1992 more than 9,200 public sector contracts were awarded, according to
Euro-Bid Watch, a consultancy which analyses the EC's contracts data.
Under EC rules, tender information is to be published in three stages.
Advance warning of forthcoming tenders in what are known as periodic
indicative notices or PINs is followed by details of individual contracts
and finally by an announcement, within 48 days of the event, that a contract
has been awarded.
The new directives call for public authorities to provide sufficient
information for all potential bidders to take part. Purchasers should not
specify the use of a particular trade-marked product to exclude other
bidders and where a European standard exists it must be used.
To avoid placing an unfair burden on purchasers the EC has set minimum
thresholds for the contracts which must be reported and has also drawn up
rules preventing unscrupulous purchasers from artificially splitting
contracts to remain below the thresholds.
A further complication is the existence of three possible procedures for
seeking bids: The 'open procedure', where all interested contractors or
suppliers may bid;
The 'restricted procedure', where only invited suppliers may tender and
The 'negotiated procedure', where the public authority negotiates the terms
of the contract with one or more suppliers.
Once the purchaser has assessed all the bids it must award the contract to
either the lowest bidder or 'the most economically advantageous' tender.
This wording allows purchasers to take into account more subjective criteria
but the factors taken into account must be published.
Nevertheless, purchasers can still bend the rules. Many unsuccessful bidders
will be unwilling to challenge a purchaser's decision for fear of losing all
future business and even when public authorities stick to the rules, the
multiplicity of purchasing organisations may put off all but the most
determined. Also, some public authorities employ cumbersome tendering
procedures which can make preparing bids expensive and time-consuming,
especially for smaller companies.
By the time details of a tender appear in the Official Journal it is often
too late, experienced suppliers warn. Companies must build up good contacts
with potential customers so that they have early warning of likely
contracts. Companies new to this field should build up experience with
public sector organisations in their own country before venturing abroad,
experts suggest. And when companies do consider other EC markets they should
start by focusing on just one or two.
*Available from government publishing organisations such as HMSO in the UK
or can be consulted at Euro Info Centres and chambers of commerce. For
information on TED contact these organisations or the EC Host Organisation,
PO Box 2373, 1023 Luxembourg. Tel: 352-34-98-12-00.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
    P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
