<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (13): Taking a longer view - Andrew Baxter finds
that performances vary but the overall picture for the sector is good / The
engineering industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR UK-based engineering companies exporting to world markets, the ability
to make good, competitively priced products seems to be half the battle. On
top of that comes perseverance and the ability to take a long-term view.
The nine general engineering companies in the Top 100 cover products ranging
from ropes to pumps and food manufacturing equipment, with household names
such as APV, Weir and Vosper Thornycroft rubbing shoulders with less-well
known companies such as Northern Ireland-based FG Wilson Engineering.
Compared with their exports in 1991, the companies' performance varied quite
widely last year, with advances leading declines by six to three. But
overall they managed to boost exports by 15.6 per cent to Pounds 1.348bn.
This is a creditable performance given the depressed state of many world
markets for engineered products.
The biggest exporter is Vickers, producer of tanks, Rolls-Royce cars,
bearings and medical equipment. It lifted total exports by 35.1 per cent
last year to Pounds 250.4m, according to the top 100 figures.
But the biggest rise in exports was notched up by a foreign company,
German-owned Robert Bosch. The vehicle components group more than doubled
its exports from Pounds 45.8m in 1991 to Pounds 93.5m last year.
The achievement is a direct result of Bosch' decision to manufacture compact
alternators at a plant at Miskin, South Glamorgan. Production began only in
January 1991 and it is projected that the factory will reach full output by
the mid-1990s.
The factory was always intended to be Bosch' single European source of
supply for compact alternators, which are lighter and more powerful than
conventional units.
Almost all last year's exports went to continental Europe, but the factory
is also selling to vehicle manufacturers in Japan.
In the post-cold war era of defence cuts, another creditable export
achievement was recorded at Vosper Thornycroft, the Southampton-based naval
shipbuilder. Exports rose by 46.9 per cent to Pounds 147.3m, with
performance boosted by two substantial orders from the Royal Navy of Oman,
for two corvettes, and the Qatar Navy for four fast strike craft.
Martin Jay, group managing director, says that the order book is standing at
a record level of Pounds 700m, of which about 95 per cent is accounted for
by the company's exports.
But he stresses that last year's successes were no flash in the pan: 'During
the last 30 years we have exported to 30 navies around the world. We have
the great benefit of selling to existing satisfied customers.'
He expresses confidence about winning further export orders. 'We are
certainly very buoyant,' he adds.
FG Wilson, meanwhile, raised its exports by 43.3 per cent to Pounds 117.4m.
The company produces diesel electric generating sets used in applications
such as stand-by power for hospitals or shopping centres, and did
particularly well last year in the Middle East and Australasia.
Last month it won the Electrical Review's export award, sponsored by GEC
Alsthom, in recognition of export sales which have grown by an average 39
per cent a year since 1987. Apart from having a product that is now
recognised worldwide, the privately-owned company's export expansion has
also been helped by being patient.
Its US subsidiary took two years to break even, and its French distributor
has yet to make a profit, but Wilson considers its presence in France to be
'absolutely critical' to its growth plans, according to the award citation.
The company has also made agreements with a number of companies which export
its gensets, including Ingersoll-Rand, Massey Ferguson and Caterpillar, to
penetrate new export markets.
The privately-owned FG Wilson employs 1,000 people, with 700 workers in
Larne. The company recently moved into an old GEC factory there,
consolidating manufacturing which used to take place at five separate
facilities.
