<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (10): Cross-border trade quickens - David
Dodwell finds there is a growing concentration of export activity in British
industry and a strong foreign presence, according to the Financial Times'
latest survey of leading UK exporters / Comment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TOTAL of 41 of the UK's Top 100 exporters are foreign owned, with 26
belonging to US parents, according to the Financial Times' latest survey of
leading exporters.
The survey also points to an increasing concentration of exporting activity
in UK industry, with the Top 100 accounting for about 47 per cent of all
exports in 1992 - up from 43 per cent in 1991. It is perhaps no accident
that the British government has campaigned hard this year to draw more small
and medium-sized companies into cross border trade.
While British Aerospace lengthened its lead as the country's leading
exporter, the main shake-up last year in the top 10 resulted from ICI hiving
off Zeneca, its former bioscience subsidiary. This led to ICI slipping from
second to seventh place. But at the same time, Zeneca entered the Top 100
for the first time in 10th place.
BP jumped from fourth to second place, on the back of a 52 per cent rise in
exports, while a 21 per cent jump by Shell lifted it into third place. Ford
slipped down to fourth position after its exports slumped by 19 per cent.
It is notable that the top 10 accounted for exports worth Pounds 25.4bn, or
more than 23 per cent of the UK's total Pounds 108.3bn exports in 1992.
More than seven out of every 10 exporters saw an improvement in exports.
This was a sharp improvement from 1991, when seven of the top 10 reported a
fall in overseas sales, and illustrates the early signs of British
industry's emergence from recession.
The performance was largely unaffected by sterling's devaluation against
most European currencies in September last year. The effects of devaluation
will only have become apparent during 1993.
For those in the UK who share US President Clinton's concern over 'jobless
growth', the survey shows that job losses continued even as exports
recovered. A surprising 79 of the Top 100 exporters cut their workforce last
year.
Only two companies added significantly to their labour force: BTR did so
because of its takeover of Hawker Siddeley late in 1991, and Nissan also
created more jobs as it moved to full production at its new car plant in
Swindon.
After entering the Top 100 in 14th place in 1991, Nissan edged up to 13th
place in 1992, hoisting exports by 33.7 per cent to Pounds 911m. Vauxhall,
which also leapt into the Top 100 in 16th place for the first time in 1991,
edged up one place on the back of a more modest 21.6 per cent gain to Pounds
754m.
While Nissan can expect to announce further gains for 1993 as its Swindon
plant has come into full production, Vauxhall is unlikely to have maintained
its growth, as Europe's car market has floundered this year.
Another insight arising from the data is that Vauxhall imports significantly
more into the UK than it exports. In spite of being the country's 15th most
important exporter in gross terms, it is in net terms a massive importer.
Imports amounting to almost Pounds 1.5bn in cars and components make it a
net importer to the tune of Pounds 736m.
Vauxhall is far from alone in this. Many companies fail to provide relevant
data, but among those that do, British Steel's imports of Pounds 790m
trimmed its net exports to Pounds 649m, while Unilever's Pounds 834m import
bill makes it a net importer of goods worth Pounds 177m, and Conoco becomes
a net importer of goods worth Pounds 311m after imports of Pounds 736m are
deducted from its exports.
Significant increases in exports were recorded by Esso (up 23 per cent),
SmithKline Beecham (33 per cent), Compaq (28 per cent), Thorn EMI (30 per
cent), and Vickers (35 per cent).
Four companies leapt into the Top 100 for the first time: Jaguar, revealing
separate figures for the first time, entered in 23rd position with exports
of Pounds 506m; FG Wilson, the Northern Ireland-based general engineering
group, was lifted to 83nd position by its 43 per cent jump in exports to
Pounds 117m; Amerada Hess, the US controlled oils group, more than doubled
exports to Pounds 97m to enter in 94rd position; and Robert Bosch, the
German engineer squeezed into 98th position after doubling exports to Pounds
93m.
The main casualties between 1991 and 1992 were the conglomerate Trafalgar
House, whose 19.5 per cent export decline to Pounds 640m pushed it from 12th
to 20th position; Inco, the Canadian-owned metals group which slipped 17
places to 39th after exports fell 21 per cent to Pounds 318m; British
Nuclear Fuels, which tumbled 28 places to 66th after exports fell 30 per
cent to Pounds 186m; and the aerospace group Westland, which fell 25 places
to 77th as exports slipped by Pounds 35 per cent to Pounds 139m.
There were few clear sectoral trends. Food manufacturers, brewers and health
and household groups were the most consistent in reporting a rise in exports
between 1991 and 1992, but only SmithKline Beecham and Nestle saw strong
gains (They were up 33 per cent and 18 per cent respectively).
The building materials sector, which included Pilkington, saw consistent
falls in exports, while those companies defined by the Financial Times as
conglomerates - Tenneco, Hanson, and Trafalgar House - also suffered, though
not for any apparently linked reason.
In spite of their leading role as exporters, only a minority of the Top 100
were heavily dependent on exports. Just 36 exported more than half of their
turnover, while only 14 exported more than three quarters.
Most export dependent were FG Wilson (exporting 90 per cent); Caterpillar
(88 per cent); Nissan (86 per cent); Zeneca (82 per cent); and Polaroid (81
per cent).
