<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (9): Virtue of patience / A look at the approach
taken by the export sales manager of Railweight, a maker of high-tech
weighing equipment - Company profile of Gabriel Villalon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Born in Chile and a graduate of Wharton School of Business in Philadelphia,
Gabriel Villalon has worked as a specialist in risk management in
international markets and spent several years in the aluminium industry. He
has also worked in Spain.
He was headhunted by Chronos Richardson last year with a brief to improve
its export performance. Home markets had declined and the company had become
part of Staveley Industries - which also owns the well-known Salter scales
brand name - in 1990.
The company is in the high technology end of the weighing business. It sells
a system developed by Coventry University - the former Lanchester
Polytechnic - to weigh railway wagons while they are moving at speeds of up
to 70 kph. This year it has started trading as Railweight to define its
image better in its highly specialised marketplace.
In the past rail wagons had to be weighed individually while at a
standstill. This meant that trains had to be uncoupled which involved
sometimes complicated shunting operations and a great deal of time and
manpower.
Over the past quarter century, the industry worldwide has moved to devices
to save uncoupling, although most still require wagons to be at rest, thus
requiring a time and energy-consuming series of stops and starts.
Mr Villalon sells devices which measure the sheer stress produced by each
wheel of a wagon as it passes over them. A series of transducers, linked to
computers, are part of integrated system which calculates the weight of each
wagon to within acceptable ranges of accuracy for the value of the load
carried.
The main customers are railway operators and any industry shifting bulk
materials - coal, cement, steel, petro-chemicals, port operations, ores,
minerals - by train.
This means export markets have become increasingly important as the British
coal industry - a principal customer and mainstay of Railweight's domestic
markets - has declined. This pressure has also encouraged lateral thinking
about other applications: the systems involved can be used equally
successfully to exactly weigh - and quickly - the precursors and raw
materials that go into chemicals manufacture or blending operations.
Moreover, by putting a transponder in every railway wagon to identify it
electronically, every location and use of each wagon can be monitored and
managed more effectively, enabling assets to be driven harder.
Maintenance is also more easily controlled - the system can detect when the
amplitude of a signal from a railway wheel changes as it wears, so it can be
replaced before it causes the train to stop. This is an improvement on
former systems, when railway workers with a good ear went round sidings and
marshalling yards tapping wheels to find faulty ones through the note they
sounded.
Railweight now turns over Pounds 2m, 60 per cent of which is exported.
Margins are comfortable because the business operates with only 20 people in
Stockport, near Manchester Airport, outsourcing most of the materials and
components from which each individual weighing system is assembled.
'No sale is straightforward,' Mr Villalon says, 'We don't just turn up with
a box of tricks. We offer to solve problems, reduce costs and improve
efficiency.'
Mr Villalon says his market is a global one, involving any company or
nationalised industry which moves goods by rail. His general approach to
exporting is to start by identifying exactly whom he should sell to. 'I work
in close contact with embassies, consulates and the Department of Trade and
Industry to get the information we need on potential customers, agents and
so on. The next thing is to go and visit,' he says.
Mr Villalon favours chamber of commerce missions for the initial
reconnaissance. These are subsidised by the government and this helps keeps
costs down. Obligations are not onerous: a few official functions and a
compulsory debriefing so the DTI can account for its spending, but most of
the time Mr Villalon is available for visits.
Mr Villalon also finds it useful to use the British Embassy for
presentations to groups, who can see videos and displays that would be
difficult to travel with. 'When I know who I want to see, I then go back to
see them individually in their place of work.' This usually means a
follow-up trip to the country concerned.
'This is a business where results are hard to come by. I am going to Spain
soon, hopefully to clinch a deal it has taken 11 months to do. I am pursuing
another sale in Poland with a liquid petroleum gas company that we started
work on in July last year. You have to be patient and keep at it,' Mr
Villalon says.
It also helps to speak to customers in their own language. Mr Villalon says
many people do not pay enough attention to this. His origins in South
America give him a decided advantage: he is fluent in Spanish, Portuguese,
English, French and Italian and says he can 'get by' in German. A former
marriage to a Swede also gave him Swedish.
</TEXT>
