<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / FT Exporter (5): A lacklustre performance - Measures to cool
down China's economy and avoid a deficit are dampening exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER more than a decade of spectacular results on the trade front, China is
coming down to earth as it faces the threat of a trade deficit for 1993
caused by an import binge fuelling its overheating economy. Chinese
officials say they will bring trade into balance by the end of the year,
averting the first deficit since 1989. Figures for the eight months to
August suggest they will have their work cut out.
China's trade deficit grew 27 per cent to Dollars 5.73bn by the end of
August, with imports soaring Dollars 58.14bn and exports climbing only 4 per
cent to Dollars 52.41bn. This compares with a trade surplus of more than
Dollars 4bn in 1992.
But the Chinese leadership, which introduced a stabilisation programme in
mid-year to cool the economy, can take comfort from the fact that since
1979, when it launched its reform programme, exports have increased ninefold
and imports eightfold. In 1980, exports were about Dollars 18bn - less than
1 per cent of world trade and just 4 per cent of gross domestic product.
This year China wants to be among the 'Top 10' trading nations, with more
than 2 per cent of world trade and exports representing about 20 per cent of
GDP, although earlier predictions that exports would exceed Dollars 100bn
are unlikely to be fulfilled.
Among the reasons for China's lacklustre export performance this year is the
fact that a booming domestic market has proved more appealing for many
potential exporters. The diversion of investment funds away from
export-generating activities to the 'hot money' areas of real estate and
currency speculation is another factor. Further, inflation of more than 20
per cent in urban centres has pushed up costs, making certain categories of
exports less competitive.
The World Bank, in its annual study of the Chinese economy, found massive
growth in fixed investment pushed up prices of raw materials at a rate of
nearly 40 per cent in the early part of this year. Excess demand had created
bottlenecks in transport and energy supplies - factors which hindered
China's export performance.
One of the main targets of China's recent reforms, spearheaded by tough
economic czar Zhu Rongji, vice-premier in charge of the economy, has been to
rein in speculative activities and give more weight to infrastructure
development and export-generating industries.
The other burning issue for China - and for the west, which has an acute
interest in liberalisation of Chinese trade - is Beijing's step towards
re-joining the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. Progress is slow, not
only because China has a long way to go before it can be deemed
'Gatt-consistent', but also because the west wants to ensure that a new
trade juggernaut in its midst has to play by the rules.
The World Bank study exposes the task confronting China in its efforts to
conform with the minimum standards required by Gatt signatories as far as
tariff and non-tariff barriers are concerned. For example, in 1992 more than
50 per cent of China's imports were subject to some form of non-tariff
administrative control.
China's tariffs, according to the World Bank, remain higher, more numerous
and more dispersed than most other large developing countries, with 69 rates
and a standard deviation of 30 per cent, compared with 34 rates and 17 per
cent for Brazil at an identical average tariff rate.
Other hold-ups to China's Gatt entry include its managed multi-tiered
exchange rate regime. Beijing has taken several important steps towards
making the renminbi more freely convertible, but its quota system of foreign
exchange allocation through Foreign Exchange Adjustment Centres is subject
to manipulation by the authorities to the detriment of a freer trading
environment.
China's anxiety over its entry to Gatt and its annual securing of Most
Favoured Nation trading status underscore its growing dependence on the
world economy.
China has much to gain from a successful conclusion of the Uruguay Round
which, the World Bank says, could reduce protection levels in the European
Commission, the US and Japan by up to 50 per cent. In that case, the study
says, China's exports would increase by an estimated 38 per cent or Dollars
11.4bn in 1988 prices, partly due to the relatively high share of textiles
and clothing products in its total exports.
Conversely, China stands to lose much by removal of MFN and is likely to try
to satisfy requirements for renewal next year on the human rights front and
by continuing to improve market access and render its trade regulations less
opaque. Loss of MFN after June 1994, the bank says, would mean China's
annual export losses to the US would range from 42 to 96 per cent (Dollars
7bn to Dollars 15.2bn).
'On the whole, it appears that the dislocation of trade flows likely to
result from the withdrawal of China's MFN status by the US would range from
the dramatic to the disastrous,' the World Bank says. The US market, where
China enjoys a huge surplus, is critical to its plans to raise exports. Its
surplus with the US exceeded Dollars 18bn last year and hit Dollars 9.49bn
in the first half of this year.
</TEXT>
