<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Blue chips stagnant as
mid-size stocks surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US BLUE chips ended a lacklustre session little changed yesterday, although
mid-size stocks and over-the-counter issues rose to new record highs, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 0.28 at 3,593.13.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.24 higher at 461.12,
while the Amex composite finished up 2.91 at an all-time high of 470.50, and
the Nasdaq composite up 4.81 at a record 772.46. Trading volume on the NYSE
was 265m.
The stage was set for some early gains when trading in New York opened, but
they never really materialised. Although overseas markets were weaker
overnight, analysts still felt that conditions were right for a bullish
market yesterday.
They believed that sentiment would strengthen after Monday's modest advances
in stock prices, that the morning decline in long bond yields to an all-time
low of under 5.9 per cent, and that a series of better-than-expected third
quarter corporate earnings reports would all boost demand for stocks.
However, after breaking through 3,600 in the early part of the session, the
Dow fell back quickly as buying petered out. A retreat by bonds after
midday, spurred by a rise in gold and other commodities prices, did not
help, and by mid-afternoon the Dow had slipped into negative territory.
Secondary stocks traded on the American Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq
market, however, remained strong throughout the day. Among individual
stocks, brokerage issues were in demand after three of Wall Street's biggest
securities firms - Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber and Bear Stearns - all
reported record or near-record quarterly earnings that exceeded analysts'
expectations. The news lifted Merrill above Dollars 100 for the first time,
and it came as no surprise when it announced plans for a two-for-one stock
split. Merrill shares ended up Dollars 2 7/8 at Dollars 101 5/8 ,
PaineWebber up Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 34 3/8 , and Bear Stearns up Dollars
 5/8 at Dollars 24 3/4 . Also higher were Morgan Stanley, up Dollars 3 3/4
at Dollars 88 1/2 , Primerica (owner of brokerage house Smith Barney
Shearson), Dollars 1 5/8 higher at Dollars 48 1/4 , and Salomon, up Dollars
1 3/8 at Dollars 49 1/4 .
Strong earnings from Motorola, which reported third quarter net income of 92
cents a share, well above analysts' estimates, lifted the technology sector.
Motorola firmed Dollars 4 7/8 to Dollars 103 3/8 , fellow semiconductor
stock Texas Instruments added Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 66 1/2 , and Compaq
put on Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 61 1/8 . On the Nasdaq market, Wellfleet
jumped Dollars 6 1/8 to Dollars 53 1/4 in volume of 3.9m shares after
reporting a more than doubling in first quarter net income to 36 cents a
share.
Centocor climbed Dollars 3 to Dollars 14 1/4 in busy trading after the
company said tests showed that its Panorex antibody cut the cancer death
rate by 30 per cent after five years.
Canada
TORONTO prices closed solidly higher in moderate trading, as gold issues
surged on rising gold prices.
According to preliminary data, the TSE-300 composite index rose 40.04
points, or 0.98 per cent, to close at 4,107.31.
American Barrick rose 1 1/4 to 33 1/4 and Placer Dome jumped 1 to 29 3/4 .
Another gold stock, Franco-Nevada Mining, gained 1 to 70  1/2.
</TEXT>
